%I A395369 #19 May 17 2026 16:26:25
%S A395369 0,2,2,22,94,1274,13138,199482,2952716,52940378
%N A395369 a(n) is the number of pairs (A->B, B->A) of non-intersecting paths in a triangular grid ABC of side n units, such that the distance from the starting point to each point of a path is always increasing.
%C A395369 Let ABC be an equilateral triangular grid of side n containing n^2 unit equilateral triangles. The x-axis is defined along AB and the y-axis is defined along AC such that starting point A has coordinates (0,0), finishing point B has coordinates (n,0) and C is at (0,n).
%C A395369 A grid point (x,y) on a path of the moving point P satisfies the following conditions when generating string of coordinates of grid points on a valid path.
%C A395369 x + y <= n, y <= n/2 and x^2 + y^2 + x*y should increase when moving to the next grid point.
%C A395369 Symmetry can be used to transform any path from A to B into a corresponding path from B to A. In particular, if (h,k) is a point on a path from A to B, then (n-h-k,k) is the corresponding point a path from B to A.
%C A395369 Paths are disjoint if they do not share any common point other than their starting or finishing corners.
%C A395369 Paths do not need to have equal length.
%H A395369 Janaka Rodrigo, <a href="/A395369/a395369_1.txt">Python code for (P,Q) pairs of strings of coordinates</a>
%e A395369 For n = 2, there are 2 different ways of reaching to each others starting corner:
%e A395369 Grid paths from A to B:
%e A395369  P1:{(0,0), (0,1), (1,1), (2,0)},
%e A395369  P2:{(0,0), (1,0), (1,1), (2,0)},
%e A395369  P3:{(0,0), (1,0), (2,0)}.
%e A395369 Grid paths from B to:
%e A395369  Q1:{(2,0), (1,1), (0,1), (0,0)},
%e A395369  Q2:{(2,0), (1,0), (0,1), (0,0)},
%e A395369  Q3:{(2,0), (1,0), (0,0)}.
%e A395369 Set of valid pairs of grid paths:
%e A395369  {(P1,Q3), (P3,Q1)}
%e A395369 Therefore a(2) = 2.
%Y A395369 Cf. A394698, A394097, A395034.
%K A395369 nonn,walk,more,new
%O A395369 1,2
